of the industrial process and face a greater challenge to improving and expanding their economies.43 The multidimensional approach to poverty measurement better describes the daily experience of poverty. Although urban areas of the region have much less income poverty than rural areas, on multidimensional counts, the region has a significant number of people who are poor, compared with other regions. Of the 1.5 billion multidimensionally poor people living in 102 developing countries in 2016, 53.9 per cent lived in South and South-West Asia alone, East and North-East Asia South-East Asia South and South-West Asia North and Central Asia Africa Europe Latin America and Caribbean Other countries or areas Total Source: Human Development Report Office, 2017. Note: MPI calculations for regions and subregions (internal document). Estimates for urban areas do not include Argentina, Libya and Trinidad and Tobago, therefore they are based on 99 countries. Surveys for these three countries do not present the urban\u2013rural variable. The share of MPI poor people in the Pacific region is not given because data are available for only one country. Table 2.1 People in multidimensional poverty in urban areas, by region and subregion, 2016 2 7 7 8 46 8 18 5 102 71,109 33,369 814,473 2,330 541,762 423 31,727 16,079 1,511,340 4.7 2.2 53.9 0.2 35.8 0.0 2.1 1.1 100 16,341 6,255 119,061 494 103,574 176 10,226 3,661 259,795 6.3 2.4 45.8 0.2 39.9 0.1 3.9 1.4 100 Number of countries Region and subregions Number of poor people (thousands) Share of poor people (% of world) Number of urban poor people (thousands) Share of urban poor people (% of world) Eradicating Poverty and Promoting Prosperity in a Changing Asia-Pacific 21 more than the share living in Africa (at 35.8 per cent). This also holds true in urban areas. Out of the total 260 million urban people living in multidimensional poverty, the Asia-Pacific region accounts for more than half (54.7 per cent); South and South-West Asia share 45.8 per cent of the urban poor population (table 2.1).44 About one in ten people live in multidimensional poverty in urban areas of Asia and the Pacific, which is significantly less than the proportion of poor people living in both urban and rural areas (at 26 per cent).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b11b11c3-8361-4753-acdf-ad5adb821645": {"__data__": {"id_": "b11b11c3-8361-4753-acdf-ad5adb821645", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/eradicating-poverty-and-promoting-prosperity-changing-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Eradicating Poverty and Promoting Prosperity in a Changing Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/eradicating-poverty-and-promoting-prosperity-changing-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "18e904afe2c5ab6c188901d983fa30b46940d45fca936d55b445f63215ade5a9"}, "2": {"node_id": "8b841414-465b-4b6e-8e34-347e91d87fde", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/eradicating-poverty-and-promoting-prosperity-changing-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "dfa03d8443652d99bdd32f3a9c272ee2300ad4f9e23e7fa470152c0c451dc17f"}}, "hash": "28682c77d285376f945181102de814c0821f6922a1500013046df30b7aff298c", "text": "By subregion, the urban multidimensional poverty rate is much higher in South and South-West Asia, where about one in four people live in multidimensional poverty, compared to between 1 and 3 per cent in all other subregions (figure 2.1). Slum populations and transient or migrant populations form a major part of the urban poor community. Although the proportion of the overall population that resides in urban slums is smaller than it was two decades ago, the absolute number generally continues to rise in all the developing regions except Latin America and the Caribbean (figure 2.2, table 2.2).45 The increase in the number of the slum populations is much larger in upper-middle-income economies than in lower-middle-income countries (table 2.2). By 2030, it", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3ea5aa11-2676-43a9-b721-90f25adf5408": {"__data__": {"id_": "3ea5aa11-2676-43a9-b721-90f25adf5408", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/eradicating-poverty-and-promoting-prosperity-changing-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Eradicating Poverty and Promoting Prosperity in a Changing Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/eradicating-poverty-and-promoting-prosperity-changing-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "587415cb2060ee9efe3873aae9effe1e607104123bf78885de2aa91d25e6f20e"}, "3": {"node_id": "ec61b96d-9931-4bf7-981a-3de8ac7b1298", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/eradicating-poverty-and-promoting-prosperity-changing-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nati